<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">This tutorial will attempt to introduce users to both NumPy and the pygame</span>
<span class="s0">surfarray module. To beginners, the code that uses surfarray can be quite</span>
<span class="s0">intimidating. But actually there are only a few concepts to understand and</span>
<span class="s0">you will be up and running. Using the surfarray module, it becomes possible</span>
<span class="s0">to perform pixel level operations from straight python code. The performance</span>
<span class="s0">can become quite close to the level of doing the code in C.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">You may just want to jump down to the </span><span class="s1">&lt;em&gt;</span><span class="s4">&amp;quot;</span><span class="s0">Examples</span><span class="s4">&amp;quot;</span><span class="s1">&lt;/em&gt; </span><span class="s0">section to get an</span>
<span class="s0">idea of what is possible with this module, then start at the beginning here</span>
<span class="s0">to work your way up.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">Now I won't try to fool you into thinking everything is very easy. To get</span>
<span class="s0">more advanced effects by modifying pixel values is very tricky. Just mastering</span>
<span class="s0">Numeric Python (SciPy's original array package was Numeric, the predecessor of NumPy)</span>
<span class="s0">takes a lot of learning. In this tutorial I'll be sticking with</span>
<span class="s0">the basics and using a lot of examples in an attempt to plant seeds of wisdom.</span>
<span class="s0">After finishing the tutorial you should have a basic handle on how the surfarray</span>
<span class="s0">works.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;/section&gt;</span>

<span class="s1">&lt;section </span><span class="s2">id</span><span class="s3">=&quot;id1&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;h3&gt;</span><span class="s0">Surfarray Introduction</span><span class="s1">&lt;a </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;headerlink&quot; </span><span class="s2">href</span><span class="s3">=&quot;#id1&quot; </span><span class="s2">title</span><span class="s3">=&quot;Permalink to this heading&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">¶</span><span class="s1">&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">There are two main types of functions in surfarray. One set of functions for</span>
<span class="s0">creating an array that is a copy of a surface pixel data. The other functions</span>
<span class="s0">create a referenced copy of the array pixel data, so that changes to the array</span>
<span class="s0">directly affect the original surface. There are other functions that allow you</span>
<span class="s0">to access any per-pixel alpha values as arrays along with a few other helpful</span>
<span class="s0">functions. We will look at these other functions later on.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">When working with these surface arrays, there are two ways of representing the</span>
<span class="s0">pixel values. First, they can be represented as mapped integers. This type of</span>
<span class="s0">array is a simple 2D array with a single integer representing the surface's</span>
<span class="s0">mapped color value. This type of array is good for moving parts of an image</span>
<span class="s0">around. The other type of array uses three RGB values to represent each pixel</span>
<span class="s0">color. This type of array makes it extremely simple to do types of effects that</span>
<span class="s0">change the color of each pixel. This type of array is also a little trickier to</span>
<span class="s0">deal with, since it is essentially a 3D numeric array. Still, once you get your</span>
<span class="s0">mind into the right mode, it is not much harder than using the normal 2D arrays.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">The NumPy module uses a machine's natural number types to represent the data</span>
<span class="s0">values, so a NumPy array can consist of integers that are 8-bits, 16-bits, and 32-bits.</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;em&gt;</span><span class="s0">(the arrays can also use other types like floats and doubles, but for our image</span>
<span class="s0">manipulation we mainly need to worry about the integer types)</span><span class="s1">&lt;/em&gt;</span><span class="s0">.</span>
<span class="s0">Because of this limitation of integer sizes, you must take a little extra care</span>
<span class="s0">that the type of arrays that reference pixel data can be properly mapped to a</span>
<span class="s0">proper type of data. The functions create these arrays from surfaces are:</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>

<span class="s1">&lt;dd&gt;&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">Creates a 2D array </span><span class="s1">&lt;em&gt;</span><span class="s0">(integer pixel values)</span><span class="s1">&lt;/em&gt; </span><span class="s0">that reference the original surface data.</span>

<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">Here we perform a 3x3 convolution filter that will soften our image.</span>
<span class="s0">It looks like a lot of steps here, but what we are doing is shifting</span>
<span class="s0">the image 1 pixel in each direction and adding them all together (with some</span>
<span class="s0">multiplication for weighting). Then average all the values. It's no Gaussian,</span>
<span class="s0">but it's fast. One point with NumPy arrays, the precision of arithmetic</span>
<span class="s0">operations is determined by the array with the largest data type.</span>
<span class="s0">So if factor was not declared as a 1 element array of type numpy.int32,</span>
<span class="s0">the multiplications would be performed using numpy.int8, the 8 bit integer</span>
<span class="s0">type of each rgbarray element. This will cause value truncation. The soften</span>
<span class="s0">array must also be declared to have a larger integer size than rgbarray to</span>
<span class="s0">avoid truncation.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>

<span class="s1">&lt;/div&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">Lastly, we are cross fading between the original image and a solid bluish</span>
<span class="s0">image. Not exciting, but the dest image could be anything, and changing the 0.50</span>
<span class="s0">multiplier will let you choose any step in a linear crossfade between two images.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;div </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;break docutils container&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;/div&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;/div&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;/div&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">Hopefully by this point you are starting to see how surfarray can be used to</span>
<span class="s0">perform special effects and transformations that are only possible at the pixel</span>
<span class="s0">level. At the very least, you can use the surfarray to do a lot of Surface.set_at()</span>
<span class="s0">Surface.get_at() type operations very quickly. But don't think you are finished</span>
<span class="s0">yet, there is still much to learn.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;/section&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;section </span><span class="s2">id</span><span class="s3">=&quot;surface-locking&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;h3&gt;</span><span class="s0">Surface Locking</span><span class="s1">&lt;a </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;headerlink&quot; </span><span class="s2">href</span><span class="s3">=&quot;#surface-locking&quot; </span><span class="s2">title</span><span class="s3">=&quot;Permalink to this heading&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">¶</span><span class="s1">&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">Like the rest of pygame, surfarray will lock any Surfaces it needs to</span>
<span class="s0">automatically when accessing pixel data. There is one extra thing to be aware</span>
<span class="s0">of though. When creating the </span><span class="s1">&lt;em&gt;</span><span class="s0">pixel</span><span class="s1">&lt;/em&gt; </span><span class="s0">arrays, the original surface will</span>
<span class="s0">be locked during the lifetime of that pixel array. This is important to remember.</span>
<span class="s0">Be sure to </span><span class="s1">&lt;em&gt;</span><span class="s4">&amp;quot;</span><span class="s0">del</span><span class="s4">&amp;quot;</span><span class="s1">&lt;/em&gt; </span><span class="s0">the pixel array or let it go out of scope</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;em&gt;</span><span class="s0">(ie, when the function returns, etc)</span><span class="s1">&lt;/em&gt;</span><span class="s0">.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">Also be aware that you really don't want to be doing much </span><span class="s1">&lt;em&gt;</span><span class="s0">(if any)</span><span class="s1">&lt;/em&gt;</span>
<span class="s0">direct pixel access on hardware surfaces </span><span class="s1">&lt;em&gt;</span><span class="s0">(HWSURFACE)</span><span class="s1">&lt;/em&gt;</span><span class="s0">. This is because</span>
<span class="s0">the actual surface data lives on the graphics card, and transferring pixel</span>
<span class="s0">changes over the PCI/AGP bus is not fast.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;/section&gt;</span>

<span class="s0">Still, it should not be as fast as normal Surface blitting,</span>

<span class="s1">&lt;section </span><span class="s2">id</span><span class="s3">=&quot;more-advanced-numpy&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;h3&gt;</span><span class="s0">More Advanced NumPy</span><span class="s1">&lt;a </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;headerlink&quot; </span><span class="s2">href</span><span class="s3">=&quot;#more-advanced-numpy&quot; </span><span class="s2">title</span><span class="s3">=&quot;Permalink to this heading&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">¶</span><span class="s1">&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">There's a couple last things you should know about NumPy arrays. When dealing</span>
<span class="s0">with very large arrays, like the kind that are 640x480 big, there are some extra</span>
<span class="s0">things you should be careful about. Mainly, while using the operators like + and</span>
<span class="s0">* on the arrays makes them easy to use, it is also very expensive on big arrays.</span>
<span class="s0">These operators must make new temporary copies of the array, that are then</span>
<span class="s0">usually copied into another array. This can get very time consuming. Fortunately,</span>
<span class="s0">all the NumPy operators come with special functions that can perform the</span>
<span class="s0">operation </span><span class="s1">&lt;em&gt;</span><span class="s4">&amp;quot;</span><span class="s0">in place</span><span class="s4">&amp;quot;</span><span class="s1">&lt;/em&gt;</span><span class="s0">. For example, you would want to replace</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;code </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;docutils literal notranslate&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;pre&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">screen[:]</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;pre&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">=</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;pre&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">screen</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;pre&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">+</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;pre&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">brightmap</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt; </span><span class="s0">with the much faster</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;code </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;docutils literal notranslate&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;pre&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">add(screen,</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;pre&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">brightmap,</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;pre&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">screen)</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;</span><span class="s0">.</span>
<span class="s0">Anyway, you'll want to read up on the NumPy UFunc</span>
<span class="s0">documentation for more about this.</span>
<span class="s0">It is important when dealing with the arrays.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">Another thing to be aware of when working with NumPy arrays is the datatype</span>
<span class="s0">of the array. Some of the arrays (especially the mapped pixel type) often return</span>
<span class="s0">arrays with an unsigned 8-bit value. These arrays will easily overflow if you are</span>
<span class="s0">not careful. NumPy will use the same coercion that you find in C programs, so</span>
<span class="s0">mixing an operation with 8-bit numbers and 32-bit numbers will give a result as</span>
<span class="s0">32-bit numbers. You can convert the datatype of an array, but definitely be</span>
<span class="s0">aware of what types of arrays you have, if NumPy gets in a situation where</span>
<span class="s0">precision would be ruined, it will raise an exception.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">Lastly, be aware that when assigning values into the 3D arrays, they must be</span>
<span class="s0">between 0 and 255, or you will get some undefined truncating.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;/section&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;section </span><span class="s2">id</span><span class="s3">=&quot;graduation&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;h3&gt;</span><span class="s0">Graduation</span><span class="s1">&lt;a </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;headerlink&quot; </span><span class="s2">href</span><span class="s3">=&quot;#graduation&quot; </span><span class="s2">title</span><span class="s3">=&quot;Permalink to this heading&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">¶</span><span class="s1">&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">Well there you have it. My quick primer on Numeric Python and surfarray.</span>
<span class="s0">Hopefully now you see what is possible, and even if you never use them for</span>
<span class="s0">yourself, you do not have to be afraid when you see code that does. Look into</span>
<span class="s0">the vgrade example for more numeric array action. There are also some </span><span class="s1">&lt;em&gt;</span><span class="s4">&amp;quot;</span><span class="s0">flame</span><span class="s4">&amp;quot;</span><span class="s1">&lt;/em&gt;</span>
<span class="s0">demos floating around that use surfarray to create a realtime fire effect.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">Best of all, try some things on your own. Take it slow at first and build up,</span>
<span class="s0">I've seen some great things with surfarray already like radial gradients and</span>
<span class="s0">more. Good Luck.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>
